{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"79e3a66b-67fc-417b-b58f-db04f37a9175","content":"## What's happening\n\n**.NET raised its x86‑64 CPU baseline.** Starting in this release cycle, the runtime requires a higher [x86‑64 microarchitecture level](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X86-64#Microarchitecture_levels) than your 2012-era hardware supports. The levels are:\n\n| Level | Key additions | Earliest CPUs |\n|-------|--------------|---------------|\n| **v1** | SSE, SSE2 (original x86‑64) | All x86‑64 chips |\n| **v2** | SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1/4.2, POPCNT | ~2008+ (Intel Nehalem, AMD Bulldozer) |\n| **v3** | AVX, AVX2, BMI1/2, FMA | ~2013+ (Intel Haswell, AMD Excavator) |\n| **v4** | AVX‑512 | Recent server/desktop chips |\n\nPrevious .NET versions targeted **v1**. If .NET 11 now requires **v3** (AVX2/FMA — Haswell and later), your 2012 hardware (Sandy Bridge / Ivy Bridge era) would fail at startup with exactly that error, because those CPUs have AVX but **not** AVX2.\n\n## Why the other targets are fine\n\n- **Windows Arm64 (Surface Pro X)** — ARM64 has its own baseline; this is an x86‑64‑only change.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Linux Arm64)** — Same; ARM64 is unaffected.\n\n## What to do\n\n1. **Verify the gap** — on the failing node run:\n   ```bash\n   # Shows the exact CPU flags\n   grep -m1 'flags' /proc/cpuinfo | tr ' ' '\\n' | grep -E 'avx2|bmi2|fma'\n   ```\n   If nothing prints, the CPU lacks v3 instructions — confirming the issue.\n\n2. **Options:**\n   - **Upgrade the hardware** to Haswell-era (2013+) or newer — the long-term fix.\n   - **Pin those nodes to .NET 10** until they're retired.\n   - Check the .NET 11 release notes for a `DOTNET_EnableHWIntrinsic` or similar compatibility switch (historically not offered for baseline changes, but worth checking).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5a09edaa-9efe-45c7-98c7-a21d3b518e2b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets aft