r the baseline was raised to x86-64-v2 (which 2012 hardware like Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge can handle) or x86-64-v3 (which requires Haswell from 2013+). AMD complicates this since older Phenom II chips from 2012 don't support SSE4.1/SSE4.2, though newer AMD chips like Piledriver do. So \"2012 hardware\" is ambiguous depending on the specific processor. So if .NET 11 bumped the baseline to v2 or v3, that would explain why older hardware from 2012 can't run it—v3 requires Haswell-era processors from 2013 onward. The ARM64 devices aren't affected since this is specific to x86-64 architecture. I'll keep my answer focused on this CPU baseline shift without getting too granular about their specific hardware.","outputTokens":2458,"requestId":"301E:1C963A:15F44D4:18B0766:6A067ADB"},"id":"eb10864e-2b6e-44b4-951b-712c2d249a09","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:46:53.497Z","parentId":"d63b7793-b67e-4102-b8b2-ea1387ffd6b1"}
